Q2

OK, here is the DAG with the features described in the question:

dag <- dagitty(
  "
  dag
  {
  LongShift [exposure]
  LowQualityCare [outcome]
  PolicyPreferences [unobserved]
  LongShift -> LowQualityCare
  LongShift -> DoctorTired
  LongShift -> DoctorExperience
  DoctorTired -> LowQualityCare
  DoctorExperience -> LowQualityCare
  Hospital -> LongShift
  Hospital -> HospitalFunding
  Hospital -> HospitalCrowded
  HospitalFunding -> LowQualityCare
  HospitalCrowded -> LowQualityCare
  PoliciesShift -> LongShift
  PoliciesCares -> LowQualityCare
  PolicyPreferences -> PoliciesShift
  PolicyPreferences -> PoliciesCares
  }
  "
)

set.seed(11235)
ggdag_status(dag, text_col = "white", text_size = 1.4) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#720500", "#244224", "#3A5874"),
                     labels = c("Treatment", "Unobserved", "Outcome")) +
  labs(color = "Nodes") +
  theme_dag(legend.position = "top")

dag <- dagitty(

Q4

Here are the reasons why we do DAG simplifications:

  1. Unimportance: when the causal effect in question is not important or it is negligible.
  2. Redundancy: when the variables occupy the same space. For instance, in the example above, we can change GeographicRegion to two distinct variables GeographicSES and GeographicSchoolN, though the implications would remain the same.
  3. Mediators: if the variable is just a mediator, we can drop it - though I do not agree that we should drop it. Why the hell?
  4. Irrelevance: As our interest is on the causal path from the treatment to the outcome, we do not need to keep anything that does not affect that relationship - e.g., the StudentSES example above, which I dropped.
